The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Saturday, July 31, 2004 				 15% less rain but hope for more
																								New Delhi, July 30 (PTI): The country has received 15 per cent less rain this season with Delhi being the worst hit, the Met department said today.																								However, it also said the situation might improve.																								Seventeen states, including the national capital, are rain deficient while two states fall under scanty category. The rest have witnessed good rainfall, said Indian meteorological department director S.K. Subramaniam.																								Delhi has received 77 per cent less rain followed by Rajasthan, which recorded 60 per cent less than in the corresponding period in previous years, the weatherman said.																								Vidarbha (34 per cent), the Northeast (28 per cent) and central India, which recorded 21 per cent below normal, are the other rain deficient regions. 																								The Met office pointed out a sharp divide  some regions are parched while some others are witnessing a flood-like situation.																								Subramaniam said things might improve with two months remaining in the season. The country receives rainfall till September. We still have two months remaining and things might improve if the system gets strengthened, he said. 
